WEBVTT

1
00:00:03.380 --> 00:00:09.380
We've created a dataset, and we've created and edited some members within a dataset.

2
00:00:09.380 --> 00:00:13.380
Now let's learn a little more about working with datasets.

3
00:00:13.380 --> 00:00:15.380
Just a reminder, some of these handy commands.

4
00:00:15.380 --> 00:00:20.380
When you type save, that saves the dataset, and it remains in edit mode.

5
00:00:20.380 --> 00:00:26.380
And when you press F3, that saves the data and returns you to the previous panel.

6
00:00:26.380 --> 00:00:31.380
So if you're all done editing and you want to exit and save, just hit F3.

7
00:00:31.380 --> 00:00:34.380
If you've made a bunch of edits that you're not entirely sure about,

8
00:00:34.380 --> 00:00:40.380
and you want to exit without committing any of them, enter cancel or can for short.

9
00:00:40.380 --> 00:00:44.380
If it's configured for quit, you can also press F12.

10
00:00:44.380 --> 00:00:49.380
One command you'll probably use a lot when working on datasets is the find command.

11
00:00:49.380 --> 00:00:54.380
Find is abbreviated as F for find.

12
00:00:54.380 --> 00:00:57.380
Then after F, place your search string.

13
00:00:57.380 --> 00:01:00.380
On this screen, we're trying to find the word back.

14
00:01:00.380 --> 00:01:04.380
So we're typing F space back into the command line.

15
00:01:04.380 --> 00:01:10.380
If there are multiple occurrences of the word, you can press F5 to advance to the next one.

16
00:01:10.380 --> 00:01:15.380
The highlight command, spelled H-I-L-I-T-E,

17
00:01:15.380 --> 00:01:22.380
lets us tell the editor to set the colors and language sensitive editing features for a specific format.

18
00:01:22.380 --> 00:01:28.380
When you type highlight and hit enter, we get this menu of languages, coloring, and options.

19
00:01:28.380 --> 00:01:34.380
Here we can select our programming language, set the coloring mode, and select a few of those options.

20
00:01:34.380 --> 00:01:37.380
We select an option with a forward slash.

21
00:01:37.380 --> 00:01:44.380
So if we select the option for highlight find strings, and then we press F3 to get back to the editor,

22
00:01:44.380 --> 00:01:50.380
notice that the F back command highlights the instances of back in the editor.

23
00:01:50.380 --> 00:01:55.380
By the way, if you know the language you want a format for, you can type it out in the command line,

24
00:01:55.380 --> 00:02:01.380
like highlight JCL, and that will color the screen specifically for JCL.

25
00:02:01.380 --> 00:02:03.380
A couple of quick notes on this.

26
00:02:03.380 --> 00:02:10.380
Some of the highlight formatting options need to be enabled by the installer or person who maintains your ISPF installation.

27
00:02:10.380 --> 00:02:16.380
So if you're on a different system and things look a little bit different, that could be why.

28
00:02:16.380 --> 00:02:19.380
Also, these options are only available in the edit mode.

29
00:02:19.380 --> 00:02:23.380
If you're browsing a file, you won't see these colors.

30
00:02:23.380 --> 00:02:28.380
A lot of times when something doesn't work right, you get an error, and the message might say,

31
00:02:28.380 --> 00:02:32.380
error detected at line 50, column 42, or something like that.

32
00:02:32.380 --> 00:02:37.380
And we can easily see what line we're at because we have the numbers on the left side of the screen there,

33
00:02:37.380 --> 00:02:40.380
but what about that error at column 42?

34
00:02:40.380 --> 00:02:44.380
Are we supposed to sit there and count out one, two, three, four, five?

35
00:02:44.380 --> 00:02:45.380
Of course not.

36
00:02:45.380 --> 00:02:49.380
You can bring up a column guide, and you can actually do this one of two ways.

37
00:02:49.380 --> 00:02:56.380
Type calls, C-O-L-S, up in the command line area, and you get a little ruler that pops up,

38
00:02:56.380 --> 00:02:59.380
and it will always be there at the top of your screen for you.

39
00:02:59.380 --> 00:03:04.380
That's pretty handy, but what if I really only want to show a column guide for one line?

40
00:03:04.380 --> 00:03:09.380
Type calls, C-O-L-S, over the line number you want the column guide for,

41
00:03:09.380 --> 00:03:13.380
and it will insert one in the editor right above it.

42
00:03:13.380 --> 00:03:16.380
Now, this does not show up in the actual data set.

43
00:03:16.380 --> 00:03:22.380
You'll notice it doesn't have a record number over there, but as you scroll up and down, it moves with the data.

44
00:03:22.380 --> 00:03:27.380
So two styles of creating column guides, and those will definitely come in handy.

45
00:03:27.380 --> 00:03:31.380
We looked at find, and we also have a change command.

46
00:03:31.380 --> 00:03:34.380
This can be used to replace a string of characters with another,

47
00:03:34.380 --> 00:03:40.380
like if we wanted to change all instances of one, two, three, four with five, six, seven, eight.

48
00:03:40.380 --> 00:03:45.380
To use the change command, just enter change, followed by what you want to change.

49
00:03:45.380 --> 00:03:48.380
Followed by what you want to change it with.

50
00:03:48.380 --> 00:03:54.380
If you want to change all instances, follow that with all, otherwise it will only change the next one.

51
00:03:54.380 --> 00:04:00.380
And there's a whole lot of options you can use for the change command, but for now, we're just going to keep it simple.

52
00:04:00.380 --> 00:04:03.380
Up next is the bounds command.

53
00:04:03.380 --> 00:04:05.380
This comes in handy from time to time.

54
00:04:05.380 --> 00:04:13.380
Let's say we want to issue a change command, but we only want to change data located between the first and 25th column.

55
00:04:13.380 --> 00:04:21.380
Sounds tricky, but with the bounds command, we can type bounds space one, space 25,

56
00:04:21.380 --> 00:04:26.380
and now our change command is limited to the area in the first 25 columns.

57
00:04:26.380 --> 00:04:32.380
To set it back, just type bounds with nothing after it and hit enter, and it will go back to default.

58
00:04:32.380 --> 00:04:36.380
Say you want to copy or move an entire data set somewhere else.

59
00:04:36.380 --> 00:04:42.380
One way of doing this is with the move copy utility, and I'm going to show you a shortcut of how to get there.

60
00:04:42.380 --> 00:04:50.380
It's in the utility section, which is option three, and within there, move copy utility is option number three.

61
00:04:50.380 --> 00:04:55.380
Since we know this, we can get there by going to 3.3.

62
00:04:55.380 --> 00:04:59.380
It'll jump us directly there without needing to stop at the screen in between.

63
00:04:59.380 --> 00:05:07.380
So from the main screen, we're going to type 3.3, and that puts us at the move copy utility.

64
00:05:07.380 --> 00:05:14.380
And we can actually jump directly from any panel to any other panel by putting an equals in front of that.

65
00:05:14.380 --> 00:05:19.380
So equals 3.3 or whatever in the command line.

66
00:05:19.380 --> 00:05:21.380
So no need to go back to that main panel.

67
00:05:21.380 --> 00:05:24.380
That should save us quite a bit of time.

68
00:05:24.380 --> 00:05:26.380
All right, moving and copying.

69
00:05:26.380 --> 00:05:31.380
Put either an M or a C for move or copy on the command line.

70
00:05:31.380 --> 00:05:39.380
Then either use the project group type fields to specify your data set or type out the name of the data set on the name line.

71
00:05:39.380 --> 00:05:48.380
Note that you can use the member field to specify a single member, or you can use an asterisk or splat to specify all members.

72
00:05:48.380 --> 00:05:54.380
You can also use a pattern like L splat to tell it only members that start with an L.

73
00:05:54.380 --> 00:05:57.380
Hit enter, and then the next screen will come up.

74
00:05:58.380 --> 00:06:03.380
Fill out the name of the target data set, where it's going, and hit enter.

75
00:06:03.380 --> 00:06:06.380
And the copy or move will begin.

76
00:06:07.380 --> 00:06:09.380
Renaming a data set is fairly similar.

77
00:06:09.380 --> 00:06:18.380
Using option 3.2, the data set utility panel, enter the old data set name and specify an R on the command line.

78
00:06:18.380 --> 00:06:20.380
The next screen will prompt you for the new name.

79
00:06:20.380 --> 00:06:23.380
Hit enter, and there you go.

80
00:06:23.380 --> 00:06:30.380
If you want to rename a member, not the entire data set, use option 3.1 for library utilities.

81
00:06:30.380 --> 00:06:38.380
Fill out all these fields or fully spell out the name of the member in the other partitioned or sequential data set field.

82
00:06:38.380 --> 00:06:42.380
And just follow the prompts, which by now should seem pretty familiar.

83
00:06:42.380 --> 00:06:46.380
Deleting data set members, that's also done in 3.1.

84
00:06:46.380 --> 00:06:49.380
Just use the command D for delete.

85
00:06:49.380 --> 00:06:55.380
Depending on how your ISPF is configured, it may or may not ask you if you're sure you want to delete those members.

86
00:06:55.380 --> 00:06:57.380
Hey, better safe than sorry.

87
00:06:57.380 --> 00:07:04.380
One more thing, we looked at the data set list utility earlier, which can be found at option 3.4.

88
00:07:04.380 --> 00:07:14.380
And we saw how you can get a listing of the members of a data set by typing out a qualifier or series of qualifiers into the dsnamelevel field and hitting enter.

89
00:07:14.380 --> 00:07:23.380
Now, check this out. When the listing comes up, we can not only edit and view the members from here by placing an E or a V into the command area,

90
00:07:23.380 --> 00:07:26.380
but we can also rename them with an R.

91
00:07:26.380 --> 00:07:32.380
Delete with a D, copy with a C-O, move with an M-O, and more.

92
00:07:32.380 --> 00:07:36.380
A fuller listing of these commands is in a file attached to this lesson.

93
00:07:36.380 --> 00:07:41.380
So that's that. You've learned how to create and manage data sets and members.

94
00:07:41.380 --> 00:07:45.380
You're ready to take on the world of data sets, at least.
